<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,500,1029]" pageId="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,489,607,632]" pageId="4">Taxonomic observations</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[504,764,608,632]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delineata">
<emphasis box="[504,764,608,632]" italics="true" pageId="4">Blepharidina delineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, known from a single female (
<figureCitation box="[1114,1183,607,632]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1848,1871]" captionTargetBox="[160,1431,198,1818]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,195,1824]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Blepharidina s. str. species habitus: 1, B. aliquantula sp. nov., ♂ holotype; 2, B. bimbiensis (Bechyné), ♂ lectotype; 3, B. burtli (Bryant), ♂ from Manjoni, Tanzania; 4, B. carinata (Bryant), ♂ lectotype; 5, B. delineata (Bryant), ♀ lectotype; 6, B. guttulata (Baly), ♂ from Zamibuo, Angola; 7, B. himba sp. nov., ♂ holotype; 8, B. intermedia (Jacoby), ♂ from Kindwitvi, Tanzania; 9, B. kasigauensis sp. nov., ♂ holotype; 10, B. kenyana sp. nov., ♂ holotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618637/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), is similar to females of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[184,280,644,668]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burtli">
<emphasis box="[184,280,644,668]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. burtli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in size, general shape, and color pattern. However, differences in spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[1210,1344,644,669]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–67" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1377,1400]" captionTargetBox="[170,1421,221,1339]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,193,1356]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 55–67. Blepharidina s. str. species spermatheca: 55, B. burtli (Bryant), lectotype; 56, B. carinata (Bryant), paralectotype from Angola; 57, B. delineata (Bryant), lectotype; 58, B. guttulata (Baly) lectotype; 59, B. intermedia (Jacoby), from Bagamoyo, Tanzania; 60, B. macarthuri (Bryant), from Usambara, Tanzania; 61, B. matabelelandensis sp. nov., paratype from Lonely, Zimbabwe; 62, B. ornaticollis (Jacoby), from Ramisi River, Kenya; 63, B. partita (Jacoby), from Huila region, Angola; 64, ditto, from Democratic Republic of The Congo; 65, B. picta (Kolbe), from Lindi region, Tanzania; 66, B. regalini sp. nov., paratype from Taveta, Kenya; 67, B. rudeli (Weise), lectotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618653/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Figs 55, 57</figureCitation>
) do not allow to think about a real affinity between these two species. The spermatheca of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[1092,1228,680,704]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delineata">
<emphasis box="[1092,1228,680,704]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. delineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1245,1327,679,704]" captionStart="FIGURES 55–67" captionStartId="17.[151,264,1377,1400]" captionTargetBox="[170,1421,221,1339]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[151,1436,193,1356]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURES 55–67. Blepharidina s. str. species spermatheca: 55, B. burtli (Bryant), lectotype; 56, B. carinata (Bryant), paralectotype from Angola; 57, B. delineata (Bryant), lectotype; 58, B. guttulata (Baly) lectotype; 59, B. intermedia (Jacoby), from Bagamoyo, Tanzania; 60, B. macarthuri (Bryant), from Usambara, Tanzania; 61, B. matabelelandensis sp. nov., paratype from Lonely, Zimbabwe; 62, B. ornaticollis (Jacoby), from Ramisi River, Kenya; 63, B. partita (Jacoby), from Huila region, Angola; 64, ditto, from Democratic Republic of The Congo; 65, B. picta (Kolbe), from Lindi region, Tanzania; 66, B. regalini sp. nov., paratype from Taveta, Kenya; 67, B. rudeli (Weise), lectotype." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618653/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
) is easily recognizable by the elongate ductus and the very short and apically rounded distal part, distinctly bent from the piriform basal part. Other characters useful for distinguishing 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[875,1014,752,776]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delineata">
<emphasis box="[875,1014,752,776]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. delineata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are: the lateral margin of pronotum almost straight and entirely visible in dorsal view (moderately sinuate (
<figureCitation box="[950,1034,788,813]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–33" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1899,1922]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[150,1436,193,1878]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 26–33. Blepharidina s. str. species pronotum and basal part of elytra, in lateral view: 26, B. aliquantula sp. nov.; 27, B. burtli (Bryant); 28, B. kasigauensis sp. nov.; 29, B. kenyana sp. nov.; 30, B. knighti (Bryant); 31, B. ornaticollis (Jacoby); 32, B. picta (Kolbe); 33, B. regalini sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618643/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
), with antero-lateral part not visible in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[184,282,824,848]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burtli">
<emphasis box="[184,282,824,848]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. burtli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); pronotal surface with a complete medial stria of punctures touching both posterior and anterior margins) (incomplete (
<figureCitation box="[420,508,860,885]" captionStart="FIGURES 26–33" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1899,1922]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[150,1436,193,1878]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 26–33. Blepharidina s. str. species pronotum and basal part of elytra, in lateral view: 26, B. aliquantula sp. nov.; 27, B. burtli (Bryant); 28, B. kasigauensis sp. nov.; 29, B. kenyana sp. nov.; 30, B. knighti (Bryant); 31, B. ornaticollis (Jacoby); 32, B. picta (Kolbe); 33, B. regalini sp. nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618643/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[566,666,860,884]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burtli">
<emphasis box="[566,666,860,884]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. burtli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); elytral surface with larger points and more distinctly carinate interstriae (with smaller points and flatter interstriae (
<figureCitation box="[749,831,895,920]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–37" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1221,1244]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,213,1182]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,213,1182]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 34–37. Blepharidina s. str. species elytra, in lateral view: 34, B. burtli (Bryant); 35, B. carinata (Bryant); 36, B. knighti (Bryant); 37, B. picta (Kolbe)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618645/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bryant" baseAuthorityYear="1944" box="[875,968,896,920]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Blepharidina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="burtli">
<emphasis box="[875,968,896,920]" italics="true" pageId="4">B. burtli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Morphometry in Appendix 2.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,500,1029]" box="[199,1230,932,957]" pageId="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,932,957]" pageId="4">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[359,460,932,957]" name="Tanzania" pageId="4">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[475,558,932,957]" captionStart="FIGURES 68–69" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1661,1684]" captionTargetBox="[151,1423,374,1634]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,374,1640]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 68–69. Blepharidina s. str. species distribution. Vegetation types are from Sayre et al. (2013)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2618655/files/figure.png" pageId="4">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
). Possibly Northern-Eastern Afrotropical (NEA) chorotype.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,500,1029]" pageId="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,392,967,992]" pageId="4">Ecological notes</emphasis>
